# Field-Test Plan and Deferred Backlog

The system is built enough. This document exists to *stop* building for a while
and instead run the system on real work, gather signal cheaply, and let evidence
-- not speculation -- decide what gets built next. Everything below is
deliberately low-effort; if maintaining this plan becomes a chore, that itself is
a finding (the process is too heavy).

Guiding rule: *do not build a deferred feature until its listed trigger actually
fires.*

- - -

## Feedback gathering

Keep it to one habit so it actually happens:

- *Cross-cutting friction* (about the format, template, or workflow) -> append
  one dated line to `FEEDBACK.log` at the repo root. Free-form. Example:
  `2026-07-11  safety section feels redundant with the top hazard line on cold protocols`
- *File-specific friction* (about one protocol) -> add a single-line
  `{% FEEDBACK: ... %}` comment in that file (stripped on render, greppable).

That is the whole system. Do not build a form or a tracker. Review the log at
the cadence below.

```
grep -rn "FEEDBACK" *.dj FEEDBACK.log 2>/dev/null   # collect all feedback
```

## Usage tracking (cheap metrics only)

Everything measurable from git and grep -- no instrumentation. Run occasionally,
not obsessively:

```
ls *_*.dj | wc -l                                  # protocols authored
grep -l "status=active"  *_*.dj | wc -l            # promoted to active
grep -l "status=draft"   *_*.dj | wc -l            # still draft
grep -rc "REVIEW" *.dj | grep -v ':0'              # files with open REVIEW flags
git log --oneline --since="4 weeks ago" | wc -l    # activity
```

The single most informative number: *open REVIEW flags trending down* means
conversions are being finished; flat or rising means the backlog is not being
worked.

## Trials to run

Concrete, each produces a specific signal. Do the cheap ones first.

| # | Trial | Signal it produces |
|---|-------|--------------------|
| T1 | Convert 5-10 representative legacy PDFs with `CONVERT_PROMPT.txt`; diff every quantity against the source | Conversion-prompt fidelity + failure modes; is REVIEW catching gaps or is it fabricating? |
| T2 | Cold-follow: run one bench task from the rendered PDF only, no original at hand | Whether the format is actually usable at the bench, not just tidy on screen |
| T3 | Fresh-machine render: clone elsewhere, `make` | Toolchain portability; validates the pandoc >= 3.1.8 assumption in the wild |
| T4 | Author one `assays_*` protocol (a different family) | Does the skeleton and note-density generalize beyond preps? |
| T5 | Adversarial input: feed the convert prompt deliberately garbled OCR | Does it flag-and-omit rather than invent? (the critical failure mode) |
| T6 | `make share` a PDF to a labmate | Provenance stamp + readability for an outside reader |

::: note
T1 and T5 together are the real test of the conversion prompt. Spend review time
diffing *numbers*, not prose -- a silent unit or quantity error is invisible and
is the only kind that ruins an experiment.
:::

## Questions to answer with evidence

Resolve these from use, not from more design discussion up front:

- Does the `preps/assays/calculators/genetics` family taxonomy fit every
  protocol, or do some feel forced? (signal: frequency of REVIEW on `family`)
- Are the six admonition types the right set -- any consistently unused, any
  repeatedly wanted? (signal: `grep -ho ':::[a-z ]*' *.dj | sort | uniq -c`)
- Is Safety-after-Purpose working, or do cold protocols make it feel like
  boilerplate?
- Did removing the per-file djot legend confuse anyone editing source, now that
  it lives only in the README?
- Is the step + note density sustainable across ~180 files, or too heavy to
  maintain?
- Do you actually render and share, or mostly read source? (decides whether the
  Makefile/CSS earn their keep)
- Any real "which version did I use" confusion from git-only versioning (no
  version in filenames)?
- At what file count does the flat directory stop being comfortable in `ls`?

## Deferred features (parked until trigger fires)

| Feature | Build it when... | Notes |
|---------|------------------|-------|
| `make check` target + git pre-commit hook (uses `check-djot.mjs`) | you commit a malformed `.dj`, or start bulk conversion | cheapest to add; likely first to graduate |
| `lw protocol` subcommand (list protocols, link to experiments) | >~20 active protocols AND you regularly hunt "which protocol for this experiment" | hooks (`{% lw: %}`, naming) already exist |
| Compilation / includes for shared steps (Quarto `{{< include >}}`) | the same sub-method is duplicated in >~5 files and drifts | costs djot simplicity; only if duplication becomes real pain |
| In-document PDF footer provenance stamp | you share PDFs externally often and filename stamps are not enough | filename stamp via `make share` covers most cases |
| CI render / auto-publish HTML | several people consume rendered docs and manual `make` is a bottleneck | |
| Cross-protocol index / tag search | >~50 protocols and `ls`/`grep` stop finding things fast | |
| Swap xelatex -> typst | xelatex build time or dependency weight becomes annoying | one Makefile variable |
| Metadata linter (enforce family/status/types vocab) | metadata drift observed across files | trivial once it matters |

::: warning
Resist building from this table because a feature is interesting. Each row has a
trigger for a reason: the point of the field-test period is to find out which
triggers actually fire. Most may not.
:::

## Review cadence and exit criteria

Reconvene once, after whichever comes first: ~20 protocols authored, or ~1 month
of real use. At that review:

1. Read `FEEDBACK.log` and all `{% FEEDBACK %}` / `REVIEW` flags.
2. Look at the usage metrics and the trial results.
3. Answer as many of the open questions as the evidence allows.
4. Only then, promote any deferred features whose triggers have fired -- and
   note which triggers did not, so they stay parked.

If little friction showed up, the correct outcome is to change nothing and keep
using it.
